<DOC><DOCNO> AP890506-0044 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 0601EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-India-Gas     05-06 0202</FIRST><SECOND>PM-India-Gas,0208</SECOND><HEAD>207 Hospitalized from Chlorine Gas Leak</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Chlorine gas that leaked from afertilizer company's tanker truck enveloped parts of a denselypopulated suburb and nearby bus station, injuring more than 200people, police said today.   The gas spewed Friday night for two hours from one of fivechlorine drums carried by the tanker, said a police official whocannot be identified under briefing rules.   The driver and his companion, apparently overwhelmed by thefumes, abandoned the tanker near a bus station, The Times of Londonnewspaper said. Most of the victims were waiting passengers, theEnglish-language newspaper said today.   Police said 207 people were admitted to six hospitals, and that151 of them were discharged today.   Many of the victims, who reported irritation in the eyes, noseand throat, had fainted but were ``out of danger now,'' said M.P.Khare, a physician who heads a government hospital where 77 peoplewere admitted.   The Times of India newspaper quoted the engineers of the company_ Shriram Foods and Fertilizers Industries _ as saying the leak wascaused by a faulty safety valve of the one-ton-capacity drum.   Officials of the company were not available for comment.</TEXT></DOC>